en The road centerline file for Stearns County was developed in three phases:
Phase 1: 1998- GeoComm, Inc was hired to utilize the base centerline file from Minnesota Department of Transportation (MNDOT). GeoComm assigned MSAG valid street names and address ranges to the existing line segments. GeoComm did not adjust the positional accuracy of the road segments. The current Master Street Address Guide (MSAG) and the Stearns County Emergency Atlas were utilized as resources for the assignment of the street names and address ranges. No field verification was done or missing road segments added. An additional polygon data set depicting the Emergency Service Zones was developed based on the MSAG reference and resource hard copy maps provided by the county. The data sets are in ESRI shape file format.
Phase 2: In 1999, Stearns County contracted with The Lawrence Group to complete phase 2 of the county's E-911 roads mapping. This phase required the mapping vendor to spatially adjust existing roads to the right-of-way in the completed portions of the Stearns County Parcel Data set, add missing road segments, verify naming conventions, and verify that all roads were snapped together. This phase also required the addition of attributes require by the county's new Computer-Aided-Dispatch software
Phase 3: Nov, 2002. GeoComm, Inc was contracted to complete the spatial adjustment of the road centerline to the positional accuracy of the Stearns County parcel map data (See Metadata for the parcel data for accuracy level). Stearns County provided the current parcel map data, current road centerline, boundary file, Emergency Atlases with Emergency Service Zones, current Master Street Address Guide, 911 data base possibly from 2000, and aerial photos for resources. The road centerline segments were adjusted within the right of way on the parcel layer. If the right of way could not be identified, the air photo was reviewed to determine the location of the segment(s). If the location of the road could not be determined from the aerial photos, the road was field verified and GPS was used. GeoComm did not compare the address ranges in the parcel data to all street segments. If the errors were located in the certain address ranges from the parcel data through another process, GeoComm corrected the address ranges. Stearns county E-9-1-1 system for use within a dispatch mapping system that will locate wireline/wireless E911 calls and other GIS applications as well as to allow for the integration of relational data sets. Stearns County with small portions of Benton and Sherbourne County that effect the Cities of Sartell and St. Cloud

A. - Feature class codes (f_class) are generalized versions of the U.S. census bureau standards. Namely: Typical Interstates are labeled A10, Interstate HOV lanes are labeled A15 (new with Dec. '98 release), US highways A20, State highways A25, County Roads A30, City Streets A40, Ramps and Loops A63, Service Drives A64, Private Roads A66, Dormitory Walkways A71, and Restricted Access A98. As of release 2.2b (a mid-quarter update on August 5, 1998), US highways and State Highways were split into two distinct feature class codes of A20 (US Highways) and A25 (State Highways).

Phase 1: Address range information was taken from several sources. Primarily the address ranges from the MSAG were used. The addressing system for Stearns County developed was based on a grid system utilizing the section lines as a base grid. The street segments were assigned address ranges and street names from the Stearns County Emergency Atlas address grids while utilizing the MSAG for verification and street names. No field verification was contracted for Phase 1 of the map development project. Theoretical address ranges were assigned to the street segments. Geocoding of the MSAG to the map files was completed and a report delivered to the county depicting missing street names in the map data.
Phase 2: Phase 2 continued geocoding and verification of the MSAG to maintain the minimum accuracy. The spatial adjustment of the data set to the current status of the Stearns County parcel data set increased the accuracy of the data in those areas. This phase created a hybrid of the original MNDOT data and Stearns County data.
Phase 3: GeoComm, Inc was contracted to adjust the road centerline to the positional accuracy of the Stearns County parcel map data (See Metadata for the parcel data for accuracy level). Stearns County provided the current parcel map data, current road centerline, boundary file, Emergency Atlases with Emergency Service Zones, current Master Street Address Guide, 911 data base possibly from 2000, and aerial photos for resources. The road centerline segments were adjusted within the right of way on the parcel layer. If the right of way could not be identified, the air photo was reviewed to determine the location of the segment(s). If the location of the road could not be determined from the aerial photos, the road was field verified and GPS was used. New developments were also added into the centerline data set. Street names and address ranges were entered into the new road segments if the information was provided to GeoComm by the jurisdiction. After the adjustment process the MSAG and the 2000 911 data base were geocoded against the current centerline map using the ESN boundary as the refining dataset. The geocoding of the MSAG identified any misspelled street names in the map data and any missing roads. A report showing the geocoding result was provided to Stearns County. GeoComm corrected any minor spelling errors to the fields containing the street name information. Any fallout from the geocoding process that resulted from the address range in the map data being actual address ranges and the MSAG included the all inclusive ranges were provided to Stearns County. The 2000 911 data base was geocoded against the road centerline file. All records that did not geocode were reviewed by GeoComm and supplied to the county. Minor changes were made to the address ranges in reviewing the fallout using the resources as a basis for resolving the fallout records. Resources included city/county employees and the parcel map data.
Some important issues follow in regard to the structure of the data set in regards to use within a 911 dispatch mapping system. - Segments must be broken at true intersections - Segments must be broken at ESN boundaries where applicable There are duplicate segments in cases where the street formed a boundary between two political entities (Ex. City and county) and the street had different street names and address ranges for each political entity. These segments have been identified and delivered to the county for review. The Stearns_rds set is complete as of publication date.
Variable. There are different degrees of accuracy throughout the file. Phase 3 of the project called for the alignment of the existing centerline to the positional accuracy of the right-of-way lines within the county parcel data set. In cases where new roads existed and there was no reference parcel information, GeoComm utilized GPS technology with a positional accuracy of 1-3 meters 95% of the time to collect the new street segments. The segments created using GPS technology are coded as such within the table. The Comment field is coded with a GC-F or a GC-D. The GC-F code represents all segments that were added to the county centerline file using GPS technology. The GC-D code represents new segments that were added through heads up digitizing from parcel information provided to GeoComm from the City/County. Additional character strings in the Comment field represents other information that was gathered pertaining to the new segment(s).
